---
import SiteLayout from "../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";
---

<SiteLayout
  title="CBCRisk-Black"
  description="A personalized contralateral breast cancer risk prediction model for Black women."
>
  <section class="p-8 sm:p-12 md:p-16 lg:p-24">
    <div class="max-w-8xl">

      {/* Hero */}
      <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-gray-900">
        CBCRisk-Black
      </h1>

      <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-gray-700">
        A personalized contralateral breast cancer risk prediction tool specifically tailored for Black women.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-4 flex flex-wrap gap-x-6 gap-y-2 text-sm text-gray-600">
        <span><strong>Status:</strong> Published</span>
        <span>
          <strong>Role:</strong> PhD student (supervised by Dr. Swati Biswas and
          Dr. Pankaj Choudhury)
        </span>
        <a
          href="https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10549-022-06612-5"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="font-medium underline"
        >
          Journal article
        </a>
      </div>

      {/* At a glance */}
      <div class="mt-10 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4 text-sm">
        <div><strong>Domain:</strong> Cancer risk prediction</div>
        <div><strong>Population:</strong> Black women with unilateral breast cancer</div>
        <div><strong>Outcome:</strong> Absolute risk of developing contralateral breast cancer (CBC)</div>
        <div><strong>Methods:</strong> Absolute risk prediction model, internal validation</div>
        <div><strong>Deliverable:</strong> Publicly available CBC risk prediction tool</div>
      </div>

      {/* Background */}
      <div class="mt-12">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">Background</h2>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 text-gray-700">
          <li>
            Black breast cancer (BC) survivors have a higher risk of developing CBC.
          </li>
          <li>
            Existing risk prediction tools were largely developed using data from predominantly White populations, limiting their clinical usefulness for Black women.
          </li>
          <li>
            Our project addresses this gap by developing an absolute risk prediction model, CBCRisk-Black, specifically for Black BC patients.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      {/* Methods */}
      <div class="mt-10">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">Methods</h2>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 text-gray-700">
          <li>
            Employed a matched lasso logistic regression model for estimating relative risks (RR) using BCSC data on 744 Black women (186 cases).
          </li>
          <li>
            Combined RR with relevant hazard rates from SEER data and attributable risks to obtain absolute risks.
          </li>
          <li>
            Six-fold cross-validation is used to internally validate CBCRisk-Black.
          </li>
          <li>
            Compared CBCRisk-Black with CBCRisk, an existing CBC risk prediction model, using area under the ROC curve.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

{/* Results */}
<div class="mt-10">
  <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">Results</h2>

  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-12 gap-6 items-start">
    {/* Left: bullets */}
    <div class="lg:col-span-6">
      <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 text-gray-700">
        <li>
          CBCRisk-Black has four risk factors: breast density, family history of BC, first BC tumor size, and age at first diagnosis of BC.
        </li>
        <li>
          The model demonstrated good discrimination for predicting contralateral breast cancer risk..
        </li>
        <li>
          Performance was improved relative to existing general-population model, CBCRisk, when applied to Black women.
        </li>
        <li>
          AUC for 3- and 5-year predictions are 0.72 and 0.65 for CBCRisk-Black while those are 0.65 and 0.60 for CBCRisk.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>

{/* Right: image */}
<div class="lg:col-span-6">
  <figure class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-gray-100 p-3 shadow-sm">
    <img
      src="/images/CBCRiskBlack.png"
      alt="CBCRisk-Black model performance and calibration results"
      class="w-full h-auto rounded-md"
      loading="lazy"
    />
    <figcaption class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-600 text-center">
      Figure: Discrimination performance of CBCRisk-Black and CBCRisk for
      predicting absolute risk of CBC in Black women.
    </figcaption>
  </figure>
</div>
</div>
</div>
      {/* Takeaways */}
      <div class="mt-10">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">Takeaways</h2>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 text-gray-700">
          <li>
            Population-specific risk modeling can improve clinical decision
            support.
          </li>
          <li>
            CBCRisk-Black provides more reliable risk estimates for Black women
            considering surveillance and treatment options.
          </li>
          <li>
            The framework highlights the importance of equity-aware model
            development in cancer risk prediction.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      {/* Citation */}
      <div class="mt-12 text-sm text-gray-600">
        <strong>Citation:</strong><br />
        Sajal IH, Chowdhury M, Wang T, Euhus D, Choudhary P, Biswas S.
        <em>
          CBCRisk-Black: A Personalized Contralateral Breast Cancer Risk
          Prediction Model for Black Women.
        </em>
        Breast Cancer Research and Treatment, 2022.
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>
</SiteLayout>
